description:
DSResult.snapshot is typed as `unknown` (types.ts:53). Every consumer does `result.snapshot as BSTNode | null` — 102 unchecked casts across DataStructuresModule.tsx. This is the foundational type-safety hole.

Fix: Make DSResult generic:
```typescript
export interface DSResult<T = unknown> {
  steps: DSStep[];
  snapshot: T;
}
```
Then type each engine: `dsBstInsert(...): DSResult<BSTNode | null>`. All 102 `as` casts become unnecessary — TypeScript infers the snapshot type.

This is the single highest-impact type change possible.

ActiveDS at DataStructuresModule.tsx:235 is a manually maintained 33-member string union. Adding a new DS to DS_CATALOG does NOT update ActiveDS — TypeScript gives no error. handleOperation/handleRandom/handleReset switches have `default: return prev` which silently swallows missing cases.

Fix:
```typescript
// index.ts
export const DS_CATALOG = [...] as const satisfies readonly DSConfig[];
// types.ts or module
type ActiveDS = typeof DS_CATALOG[number]['id'];
```
Also change switch defaults from `return prev` to `const _exhaustive: never = prev.activeDS; return prev;` to catch missing cases at compile time.

Extensibility test: currently 1/9 steps caught by TypeScript. After fix: 9/9.

All 33 engine files use module-level `let _stepId = 0` with `resetStepId()`. The vector-clock chain at DataStructuresModule.tsx:5841-5846 calls vectorClockSend then vectorClockReceive without reset between them — step IDs collide. This is an ACTIVE bug, not theoretical.

Fix: Create a pure step recorder factory:
```typescript
export function createStepRecorder() {
  let id = 0;
  return {
    step(desc: string, mutations: DSMutation[]): DSStep {
      return { id: id++, description: desc, mutations };
    }
  };
}
```
Each operation creates its own recorder. No global state, no reset ceremony, safe for chained calls.

MerkleNode uses optional fields (data?, left?, right?) instead of a discriminated union. BPlusNode correctly uses `kind: 'leaf' | 'internal'` — the only well-typed tree node in the module.

Fix MerkleNode to match:
```typescript
interface MerkleLeafNode { id: string; kind: 'leaf'; hash: string; data: string; }
interface MerkleInternalNode { id: string; kind: 'internal'; hash: string; left: MerkleNode; right: MerkleNode; }
type MerkleNode = MerkleLeafNode | MerkleInternalNode;
```
Consumers use `if (node.kind === 'leaf')` with full narrowing instead of null checks.

DSModuleState has 46 fields in a single useState. handleOperation is a 580-line switch that repeats the same state-merge pattern 102 times. The dead `applyResult` callback at line 5311 shows the developer tried to abstract this but abandoned it.

Convert to useReducer with typed actions:
```typescript
type DSAction = 
  | { type: 'SELECT_DS'; ds: ActiveDS }
  | { type: 'OPERATION'; ds: 'bst'; op: 'insert'; value: number }
  | { type: 'OPERATION'; ds: 'hash-table'; op: 'insert'; key: string; value: number }
  | { type: 'RANDOM'; ds: ActiveDS }
  | { type: 'RESET' }
  | { type: 'STEP_FORWARD' };
```
Each action handler knows the concrete types — no `snapshot as` casts needed. The reducer is a pure function, testable in isolation. Eliminates duplicate switch logic across handleOperation/handleRandom/handleReset.
